SIMPLE: wane
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wane
<hw>Wane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Waned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Waning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>wanien</ets>, AS.
<ets>wanian</ets>, <ets>wonian</ets>, from <ets>wan</ets>,
<ets>won</ets>, deficient, wanting; akin to D. <ets>wan-</ets>, G.
<ets>wahn</ets>sinn, insanity, OHG. <ets>wan</ets>, <ets>wana-</ets>,
lacking, <ets>wan<?/n</ets> to lessen, Icel. <ets>vanr</ets> lacking,
Goth. <ets>vans</ets>; cf. Gr. <?/ bereaved, Skr. <ets><?/na</ets>
wanting, inferior. <?/<?/<?/<?/. Cf. <er>Want</er> lack, and
<er>Wanton</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To be diminished; to decrease; -- contrasted with
<ant>wax</ant>, and especially applied to the illuminated part of the
moon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like the moon, aye wax ye and <qex>wane</qex>.⟦br⟧
<qex>Waning</qex> moons their settled periods keep.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To decline; to fail; to sink.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You saw but sorrow in its <qex>waning</qex> form.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Land and trade ever will wax and <qex>wane</qex> together.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir J. Child.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wane</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wane
<hw>Wane</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to decrease.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wane</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wane
<hw>Wane</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The decrease of the
illuminated part of the moon to the eye of a spectator.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Decline; failure; diminution; decrease;
declension.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An age in which the church is in its <qex>wane</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though the year be on the <qex>wane</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An inequality in a board.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Forestry)</fld> <def>The natural curvature of a log
or of the edge of a board sawed from a log.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Waney</ent>⟦br⟧
